#8282
Tutorial: Communication~
Project Twilight is a roleplaying game, so communication is key.
Here are the main ways to talk:

  \tCsay\tn \tW<message>\tn - Speak in-character to the room
  \tCoocsay\tn \tW<message>\tn - Speak out-of-character to the room
  \tCemote\tn \tW<action>\tn - Describe an action (e.g., emote smiles.)
  \tCpmote\tn \tW<action>\tn - Directed emote using a person's name
  \tCthink\tn \tW<thought>\tn - Internal dialogue (seen by some powers)
  \tCyell\tn \tW<message>\tn - Shout to the nearby area
  \tChelpline\tn \tW<message>\tn - Ask for help (heard by everyone)

Try '\tWsay Hello!\tn' or '\tWemote looks around curiously.\tn'
then go \tWnorth\tn.
~
0 8 0
E
XNUMB1~
Unnamed Room~
E
XDUMB1~
None~
E
channels~
Syntax: channels - Lists all communication channels and their current status (on/off). You can toggle channels on and off to control what you hear.~
E
helpline~
Syntax: helpline <message> - Sends a message heard by all online players. Use this if you need help and no one is in the room with you.~
E
yell~
Syntax: yell <message> - Shouts to everyone in the nearby area. Use sparingly - it is loud and disruptive.~
E
think~
Syntax: think <thought> - Internal dialogue visible to those with certain supernatural powers (Auspex, etc.). Useful for adding depth to roleplay scenes.~
E
pmote~
Syntax: pmote <action using someone's name> - A directed emote. The target sees 'you' instead of their name. Example: 'pmote nods to Bob' - Bob sees 'YourName nods to you.'~
E
emote~
Syntax: emote <action> - Performs a free-form action visible to the room. Example: 'emote leans against the wall' shows 'YourName leans against the wall.' Related commands: pmote (directed at a person), dmote (scene-setting), dpmote (directed scene-setting).~
E
oocsay~
Syntax: oocsay <message> - Speaks out-of-character to everyone in the room. Use this when you need to communicate something that is not part of the story, such as asking a game mechanics question.~
E
say~
Syntax: say <message> - Speaks in-character to everyone in the room. This is the most common form of in-character communication. Others in the room will see your character's name followed by your message.~
