#8284
Tutorial: Items and Equipment~
The world is full of objects you can interact with:

  \tCget\tn \tW<item>\tn - Pick something up
  \tCdrop\tn \tW<item>\tn - Drop something from your inventory
  \tCwear\tn \tW<item>\tn - Put on clothing or armor
  \tCwield\tn \tW<item>\tn - Ready a weapon
  \tChold\tn \tW<item>\tn - Hold an item in your hands
  \tCremove\tn \tW<item>\tn - Take off something you are wearing
  \tCinventory\tn - See what you are carrying
  \tCequipment\tn - See what you are wearing

There is a training token on the ground here. Try '\tWget token\tn',
then '\tWinventory\tn' to see it, then go \tWnorth\tn.
~
0 8 0
E
XNUMB1~
Unnamed Room~
E
XDUMB1~
None~
E
equipment~
Syntax: equipment - Lists all items you are currently wearing, wielding, or holding. Use 'inventory' to see items you are carrying but not wearing.~
E
inventory~
Syntax: inventory - Lists all items you are carrying but not currently wearing. Use 'equipment' to see what you have worn or wielded.~
E
hold~
Syntax: hold <item> - Holds an item in your hands. Useful for phones, lights, and other hand-held items.~
E
wield~
Syntax: wield <weapon> - Readies a weapon for combat. The weapon must be in your inventory.~
E
wear~
Syntax: wear <item> - Puts on a piece of clothing or armor. The item must be in your inventory. Some items can only be worn in specific locations (head, body, legs, etc.).~
E
drop~
Syntax: drop <item> - Drops an item from your inventory onto the ground.~
E
get~
Syntax: get <item> - Picks up an item from the ground. Syntax: get <item> <container> - Takes an item from inside a container. You can also use 'take' as an alternative to 'get'.~
